  62 def _assert(cond, ex_type, msg):
  63   """A polymorphic assert, works with tensors and boolean expressions.
  64 
  65   If `cond` is not a tensor, behave like an ordinary assert statement, except
  66   that a empty list is returned. If `cond` is a tensor, return a list
  67   containing a single TensorFlow assert op.
  68 
  69   Args:
  70     cond: Something evaluates to a boolean value. May be a tensor.
  71     ex_type: The exception class to use.
  72     msg: The error message.
  73 
  74   Returns:
  75     A list, containing at most one assert op.
  76   """
  77   if _is_tensor(cond):
  78     return [control_flow_ops.Assert(cond, [msg])]
  79   else:
  80     if not cond:
  81       raise ex_type(msg)
  82     else:
  83       return []

  86 def _is_tensor(x):
  87   """Returns `True` if `x` is a symbolic tensor-like object.
  88 
  89   Args:
  90     x: A python object to check.
  91 
  92   Returns:
  93     `True` if `x` is a `tf.Tensor` or `tf.Variable`, otherwise `False`.
  94   """
  95   return isinstance(x, (ops.Tensor, variables.Variable))

  98 def _ImageDimensions(image, rank):
  99   """Returns the dimensions of an image tensor.
 100 
 101   Args:
 102     image: A rank-D Tensor. For 3-D  of shape: `[height, width, channels]`.
 103     rank: The expected rank of the image
 104 
 105   Returns:
 106     A list of corresponding to the dimensions of the
 107     input image.  Dimensions that are statically known are python integers,
 108     otherwise they are integer scalar tensors.
 109   """
 110   if image.get_shape().is_fully_defined():
 111     return image.get_shape().as_list()
 112   else:
 113     static_shape = image.get_shape().with_rank(rank).as_list()
 114     dynamic_shape = array_ops.unstack(array_ops.shape(image), rank)
 115     return [
 116         s if s is not None else d for s, d in zip(static_shape, dynamic_shape)
 117     ]

 120 def _Check3DImage(image, require_static=True):
 121   """Assert that we are working with properly shaped image.
 122 
 123   Args:
 124     image: 3-D Tensor of shape [height, width, channels]
 125     require_static: If `True`, requires that all dimensions of `image` are
 126       known and non-zero.
 127 
 128   Raises:
 129     ValueError: if `image.shape` is not a 3-vector.
 130 
 131   Returns:
 132     An empty list, if `image` has fully defined dimensions. Otherwise, a list
 133     containing an assert op is returned.
 134   """
 135   try:
 136     image_shape = image.get_shape().with_rank(3)
 137   except ValueError:
 138     raise ValueError(
 139         "'image' (shape %s) must be three-dimensional." % image.shape)
 140   if require_static and not image_shape.is_fully_defined():
 141     raise ValueError("'image' (shape %s) must be fully defined." % image_shape)
 142   if any(x == 0 for x in image_shape):
 143     raise ValueError("all dims of 'image.shape' must be > 0: %s" % image_shape)
 144   if not image_shape.is_fully_defined():
 145     return [
 146         check_ops.assert_positive(
 147             array_ops.shape(image),
 148             ["all dims of 'image.shape' "
 149              'must be > 0.'])
 150     ]
 151   else:
 152     return []
 153

 155 def _Assert3DImage(image):
 156   """Assert that we are working with a properly shaped image.
 157 
 158     Performs the check statically if possible (i.e. if the shape
 159     is statically known). Otherwise adds a control dependency
 160     to an assert op that checks the dynamic shape.
 161 
 162     Args:
 163       image: 3-D Tensor of shape [height, width, channels]
 164 
 165     Raises:
 166       ValueError: if `image.shape` is not a 3-vector.
 167 
 168     Returns:
 169       If the shape of `image` could be verified statically, `image` is
 170       returned unchanged, otherwise there will be a control dependency
 171       added that asserts the correct dynamic shape.
 172     """
 173   return control_flow_ops.with_dependencies(
 174       _Check3DImage(image, require_static=False), image)
 175

 177 def _AssertAtLeast3DImage(image):
 178   """Assert that we are working with a properly shaped image.
 179 
 180     Performs the check statically if possible (i.e. if the shape
 181     is statically known). Otherwise adds a control dependency
 182     to an assert op that checks the dynamic shape.
 183 
 184     Args:
 185       image: >= 3-D Tensor of size [*, height, width, depth]
 186 
 187     Raises:
 188       ValueError: if image.shape is not a [>= 3] vector.
 189 
 190     Returns:
 191       If the shape of `image` could be verified statically, `image` is
 192       returned unchanged, otherwise there will be a control dependency
 193       added that asserts the correct dynamic shape.
 194   """
 195   return control_flow_ops.with_dependencies(
 196       _CheckAtLeast3DImage(image, require_static=False), image)

 199 def _CheckAtLeast3DImage(image, require_static=True):
 200   """Assert that we are working with properly shaped image.
 201 
 202   Args:
 203     image: >= 3-D Tensor of size [*, height, width, depth]
 204     require_static: If `True`, requires that all dimensions of `image` are
 205       known and non-zero.
 206 
 207   Raises:
 208     ValueError: if image.shape is not a [>= 3] vector.
 209 
 210   Returns:
 211     An empty list, if `image` has fully defined dimensions. Otherwise, a list
 212     containing an assert op is returned.
 213   """
 214   try:
 215     if image.get_shape().ndims is None:
 216       image_shape = image.get_shape().with_rank(3)
 217     else:
 218       image_shape = image.get_shape().with_rank_at_least(3)
 219   except ValueError:
 220     raise ValueError("'image' must be at least three-dimensional.")
 221   if require_static and not image_shape.is_fully_defined():
 222     raise ValueError('\'image\' must be fully defined.')
 223   if any(x == 0 for x in image_shape):
 224     raise ValueError(
 225         'all dims of \'image.shape\' must be > 0: %s' % image_shape)
 226   if not image_shape.is_fully_defined():
 227     return [
 228         check_ops.assert_positive(
 229             array_ops.shape(image),
 230             ["all dims of 'image.shape' "
 231              'must be > 0.'])
 232     ]
 233   else:
 234     return []

 237 def fix_image_flip_shape(image, result):
 238   """Set the shape to 3 dimensional if we don't know anything else.
 239 
 240   Args:
 241     image: original image size
 242     result: flipped or transformed image
 243 
 244   Returns:
 245     An image whose shape is at least None,None,None.
 246   """
 247 
 248   image_shape = image.get_shape()
 249   if image_shape == tensor_shape.unknown_shape():
 250     result.set_shape([None, None, None])
 251   else:
 252     result.set_shape(image_shape)
 253   return result

 256 @tf_export('image.random_flip_up_down')
 257 def random_flip_up_down(image, seed=None):
 258   """Randomly flips an image vertically (upside down).
 259 
 260   With a 1 in 2 chance, outputs the contents of `image` flipped along the first
 261   dimension, which is `height`.  Otherwise output the image as-is.
 262 
 263   Args:
 264     image: 4-D Tensor of shape `[batch, height, width, channels]` or
 265            3-D Tensor of shape `[height, width, channels]`.
 266     seed: A Python integer. Used to create a random seed. See
 267       `tf.set_random_seed`
 268       for behavior.
 269 
 270   Returns:
 271     A tensor of the same type and shape as `image`.
 272   Raises:
 273     ValueError: if the shape of `image` not supported.
 274   """
 275   return _random_flip(image, 0, seed, 'random_flip_up_down')

 279 def random_flip_left_right(image, seed=None):

 283   second dimension, which is `width`.  Otherwise output the image as-is.

 301 def _random_flip(image, flip_index, seed, scope_name):
 302   """Randomly (50% chance) flip an image along axis `flip_index`.
 303 
 304   Args:
 305     image: 4-D Tensor of shape `[batch, height, width, channels]` or
 306            3-D Tensor of shape `[height, width, channels]`.
 307     flip_index: Dimension along which to flip image. Vertical: 0, Horizontal: 1
 308     seed: A Python integer. Used to create a random seed. See
 309       `tf.set_random_seed`
 310       for behavior.
 311     scope_name: Name of the scope in which the ops are added.
 312 
 313   Returns:
 314     A tensor of the same type and shape as `image`.
 315 
 316   Raises:
 317     ValueError: if the shape of `image` not supported.
 318   """
 319   with ops.name_scope(None, scope_name, [image]) as scope:
 320     image = ops.convert_to_tensor(image, name='image')
 321     image = _AssertAtLeast3DImage(image)
 322     shape = image.get_shape()
 323     if shape.ndims == 3 or shape.ndims is None:
 324       uniform_random = random_ops.random_uniform([], 0, 1.0, seed=seed)
 325       mirror_cond = math_ops.less(uniform_random, .5)
 326       result = control_flow_ops.cond(
 327           mirror_cond,
 328           lambda: array_ops.reverse(image, [flip_index]),
 329           lambda: image,
 330           name=scope
 331       )
 332       return fix_image_flip_shape(image, result)
 333     elif shape.ndims == 4:
 334       batch_size = array_ops.shape(image)[0]
 335       uniform_random = random_ops.random_uniform(
 336           [batch_size], 0, 1.0, seed=seed
 337       )
 338       flips = math_ops.round(
 339           array_ops.reshape(uniform_random, [batch_size, 1, 1, 1])
 340       )
 341       flips = math_ops.cast(flips, image.dtype)
 342       flipped_input = array_ops.reverse(image, [flip_index + 1])
 343       return flips * flipped_input + (1 - flips) * image
 344     else:
 345       raise ValueError('\'image\' must have either 3 or 4 dimensions.')
 346

 390 def _flip(image, flip_index, scope_name):
 391   """Flip an image either horizontally or vertically.
 392 
 393   Outputs the contents of `image` flipped along the dimension `flip_index`.
 394 
 395   See also `reverse()`.
 396 
 397   Args:
 398     image: 4-D Tensor of shape `[batch, height, width, channels]` or
 399            3-D Tensor of shape `[height, width, channels]`.
 400     flip_index: 0 For vertical, 1 for horizontal.
 401 
 402   Returns:
 403     A tensor of the same type and shape as `image`.
 404 
 405   Raises:
 406     ValueError: if the shape of `image` not supported.
 407   """
 408   with ops.name_scope(None, scope_name, [image]):
 409     image = ops.convert_to_tensor(image, name='image')
 410     image = _AssertAtLeast3DImage(image)
 411     shape = image.get_shape()
 412     if shape.ndims == 3 or shape.ndims is None:
 413       return fix_image_flip_shape(image, array_ops.reverse(image, [flip_index]))
 414     elif shape.ndims == 4:
 415       return array_ops.reverse(image, [flip_index+1])
 416     else:
 417       raise ValueError('\'image\' must have either 3 or 4 dimensions.')

 420 @tf_export('image.rot90')
 421 def rot90(image, k=1, name=None):
 422   """Rotate image(s) counter-clockwise by 90 degrees.
 423 
 424   Args:
 425     image: 4-D Tensor of shape `[batch, height, width, channels]` or
 426            3-D Tensor of shape `[height, width, channels]`.
 427     k: A scalar integer. The number of times the image is rotated by 90 degrees.
 428     name: A name for this operation (optional).
 429 
 430   Returns:
 431     A rotated tensor of the same type and shape as `image`.
 432 
 433   Raises:
 434     ValueError: if the shape of `image` not supported.
 435   """
 436   with ops.name_scope(name, 'rot90', [image, k]) as scope:
 437     image = ops.convert_to_tensor(image, name='image')
 438     image = _AssertAtLeast3DImage(image)
 439     k = ops.convert_to_tensor(k, dtype=dtypes.int32, name='k')
 440     k.get_shape().assert_has_rank(0)
 441     k = math_ops.mod(k, 4)
 442 
 443     shape = image.get_shape()
 444     if shape.ndims == 3 or shape.ndims is None:
 445       return _rot90_3D(image, k, scope)
 446     elif shape.ndims == 4:
 447       return _rot90_4D(image, k, scope)
 448     else:
 449       raise ValueError('\'image\' must have either 3 or 4 dimensions.')
 450 
 451 
 452 def _rot90_3D(image, k, name_scope):
 453   """Rotate image counter-clockwise by 90 degrees `k` times.
 454 
 455   Args:
 456     image: 3-D Tensor of shape `[height, width, channels]`.
 457     k: A scalar integer. The number of times the image is rotated by 90 degrees.
 458     name_scope: A valid TensorFlow name scope.
 459 
 460   Returns:
 461     A 3-D tensor of the same type and shape as `image`.
 462 
 463   """
 464 
 465   def _rot90():
 466     return array_ops.transpose(array_ops.reverse_v2(image, [1]), [1, 0, 2])
 467 
 468   def _rot180():
 469     return array_ops.reverse_v2(image, [0, 1])
 470 
 471   def _rot270():
 472     return array_ops.reverse_v2(array_ops.transpose(image, [1, 0, 2]), [1])
 473 
 474   cases = [(math_ops.equal(k, 1), _rot90), (math_ops.equal(k, 2), _rot180),
 475            (math_ops.equal(k, 3), _rot270)]
 476 
 477   result = control_flow_ops.case(
 478       cases, default=lambda: image, exclusive=True, name=name_scope)
 479   result.set_shape([None, None, image.get_shape()[2]])
 480   return result
 481 
 482 
 483 def _rot90_4D(images, k, name_scope):
 484   """Rotate batch of images counter-clockwise by 90 degrees `k` times.
 485 
 486   Args:
 487     images: 4-D Tensor of shape `[height, width, channels]`.
 488     k: A scalar integer. The number of times the images are rotated by 90
 489       degrees.
 490     name_scope: A valid TensorFlow name scope.
 491 
 492   Returns:
 493     A 4-D tensor of the same type and shape as `images`.
 494 
 495   """
 496 
 497   def _rot90():
 498     return array_ops.transpose(array_ops.reverse_v2(images, [2]), [0, 2, 1, 3])
 499 
 500   def _rot180():
 501     return array_ops.reverse_v2(images, [1, 2])
 502   def _rot270():
 503     return array_ops.reverse_v2(array_ops.transpose(images, [0, 2, 1, 3]), [2])
 504 
 505   cases = [(math_ops.equal(k, 1), _rot90), (math_ops.equal(k, 2), _rot180),
 506            (math_ops.equal(k, 3), _rot270)]
 507 
 508   result = control_flow_ops.case(
 509       cases, default=lambda: images, exclusive=True, name=name_scope)
 510   shape = result.get_shape()
 511   result.set_shape([shape[0], None, None, shape[3]])
 512   return result

 514 @tf_export('image.transpose_image')
 515 def transpose_image(image):
 516   """Transpose image(s) by swapping the height and width dimension.
 517 
 518   See also `transpose()`.
 519 
 520   Args:
 521     image: 4-D Tensor of shape `[batch, height, width, channels]` or
 522            3-D Tensor of shape `[height, width, channels]`.
 523 
 524   Returns:
 525     If `image` was 4-D, a 4-D float Tensor of shape
 526    `[batch, width, height, channels]`
 527     If `image` was 3-D, a 3-D float Tensor of shape
 528    `[width, height, channels]`
 529 
 530   Raises:
 531     ValueError: if the shape of `image` not supported.
 532   """
 533   with ops.name_scope(None, 'transpose_image', [image]):
 534     image = ops.convert_to_tensor(image, name='image')
 535     image = _AssertAtLeast3DImage(image)
 536     shape = image.get_shape()
 537     if shape.ndims == 3 or shape.ndims is None:
 538       return array_ops.transpose(image, [1, 0, 2], name='transpose_image')
 539     elif shape.ndims == 4:
 540       return array_ops.transpose(image, [0, 2, 1, 3], name='transpose_image')
 541     else:
 542       raise ValueError('\'image\' must have either 3 or 4 dimensions.')

 545 @tf_export('image.central_crop')
 546 def central_crop(image, central_fraction):
 547   """Crop the central region of the image(s).
 548 
 549   Remove the outer parts of an image but retain the central region of the image
 550   along each dimension. If we specify central_fraction = 0.5, this function
 551   returns the region marked with "X" in the below diagram.
 552 
 553        --------
 554       |        |
 555       |  XXXX  |
 556       |  XXXX  |
 557       |        |   where "X" is the central 50% of the image.
 558        --------
 559 
 560   This function works on either a single image (`image` is a 3-D Tensor), or a
 561   batch of images (`image` is a 4-D Tensor).
 562 
 563   Args:
 564     image: Either a 3-D float Tensor of shape [height, width, depth], or a 4-D
 565       Tensor of shape [batch_size, height, width, depth].
 566     central_fraction: float (0, 1], fraction of size to crop
 567 
 568   Raises:
 569     ValueError: if central_crop_fraction is not within (0, 1].
 570 
 571   Returns:
 572     3-D / 4-D float Tensor, as per the input.
 573   """
 574   with ops.name_scope(None, 'central_crop', [image]):
 575     image = ops.convert_to_tensor(image, name='image')
 576     if central_fraction <= 0.0 or central_fraction > 1.0:
 577       raise ValueError('central_fraction must be within (0, 1]')
 578     if central_fraction == 1.0:
 579       return image
 580 
 581     _AssertAtLeast3DImage(image)
 582     rank = image.get_shape().ndims
 583     if rank != 3 and rank != 4:
 584       raise ValueError('`image` should either be a Tensor with rank = 3 or '
 585                        'rank = 4. Had rank = {}.'.format(rank))
 586 
 587     # Helper method to return the `idx`-th dimension of `tensor`, along with
 588     # a boolean signifying if the dimension is dynamic.
 589     def _get_dim(tensor, idx):
 590       static_shape = tensor.get_shape()[idx].value
 591       if static_shape is not None:
 592         return static_shape, False
 593       return array_ops.shape(tensor)[idx], True
 594 
 595     # Get the height, width, depth (and batch size, if the image is a 4-D
 596     # tensor).
 597     if rank == 3:
 598       img_h, dynamic_h = _get_dim(image, 0)
 599       img_w, dynamic_w = _get_dim(image, 1)
 600       img_d = image.get_shape()[2]
 601     else:
 602       img_bs = image.get_shape()[0]
 603       img_h, dynamic_h = _get_dim(image, 1)
 604       img_w, dynamic_w = _get_dim(image, 2)
 605       img_d = image.get_shape()[3]
 606 
 607     # Compute the bounding boxes for the crop. The type and value of the
 608     # bounding boxes depend on the `image` tensor's rank and whether / not the
 609     # dimensions are statically defined.
 610     if dynamic_h:
 611       img_hd = math_ops.to_double(img_h)
 612       bbox_h_start = math_ops.to_int32((img_hd - img_hd * central_fraction) / 2)
 613     else:
 614       img_hd = float(img_h)
 615       bbox_h_start = int((img_hd - img_hd * central_fraction) / 2)
 616 
 617     if dynamic_w:
 618       img_wd = math_ops.to_double(img_w)
 619       bbox_w_start = math_ops.to_int32((img_wd - img_wd * central_fraction) / 2)
 620     else:
 621       img_wd = float(img_w)
 622       bbox_w_start = int((img_wd - img_wd * central_fraction) / 2)
 623 
 624     bbox_h_size = img_h - bbox_h_start * 2
 625     bbox_w_size = img_w - bbox_w_start * 2
 626 
 627     if rank == 3:
 628       bbox_begin = array_ops.stack([bbox_h_start, bbox_w_start, 0])
 629       bbox_size = array_ops.stack([bbox_h_size, bbox_w_size, -1])
 630     else:
 631       bbox_begin = array_ops.stack([0, bbox_h_start, bbox_w_start, 0])
 632       bbox_size = array_ops.stack([-1, bbox_h_size, bbox_w_size, -1])
 633 
 634     image = array_ops.slice(image, bbox_begin, bbox_size)
 635 
 636     # Reshape the `image` tensor to the desired size.
 637     if rank == 3:
 638       image.set_shape([
 639           None if dynamic_h else bbox_h_size,
 640           None if dynamic_w else bbox_w_size,
 641           img_d
 642       ])
 643     else:
 644       image.set_shape([
 645           img_bs,
 646           None if dynamic_h else bbox_h_size,
 647           None if dynamic_w else bbox_w_size,
 648           img_d
 649       ])
 650     return image
 651

 653 @tf_export('image.pad_to_bounding_box')
 654 def pad_to_bounding_box(image, offset_height, offset_width, target_height,
 655                         target_width):
 656   """Pad `image` with zeros to the specified `height` and `width`.
 657 
 658   Adds `offset_height` rows of zeros on top, `offset_width` columns of
 659   zeros on the left, and then pads the image on the bottom and right
 660   with zeros until it has dimensions `target_height`, `target_width`.
 661 
 662   This op does nothing if `offset_*` is zero and the image already has size
 663   `target_height` by `target_width`.
 664 
 665   Args:
 666     image: 4-D Tensor of shape `[batch, height, width, channels]` or
 667            3-D Tensor of shape `[height, width, channels]`.
 668     offset_height: Number of rows of zeros to add on top.
 669     offset_width: Number of columns of zeros to add on the left.
 670     target_height: Height of output image.
 671     target_width: Width of output image.
 672 
 673   Returns:
 674     If `image` was 4-D, a 4-D float Tensor of shape
 675     `[batch, target_height, target_width, channels]`
 676     If `image` was 3-D, a 3-D float Tensor of shape
 677     `[target_height, target_width, channels]`
 678 
 679   Raises:
 680     ValueError: If the shape of `image` is incompatible with the `offset_*` or
 681       `target_*` arguments, or either `offset_height` or `offset_width` is
 682       negative.
 683   """
 684   with ops.name_scope(None, 'pad_to_bounding_box', [image]):
 685     image = ops.convert_to_tensor(image, name='image')
 686 
 687     is_batch = True
 688     image_shape = image.get_shape()
 689     if image_shape.ndims == 3:
 690       is_batch = False
 691       image = array_ops.expand_dims(image, 0)
 692     elif image_shape.ndims is None:
 693       is_batch = False
 694       image = array_ops.expand_dims(image, 0)
 695       image.set_shape([None] * 4)
 696     elif image_shape.ndims != 4:
 697       raise ValueError('\'image\' must have either 3 or 4 dimensions.')
 698 
 699     assert_ops = _CheckAtLeast3DImage(image, require_static=False)
 700     batch, height, width, depth = _ImageDimensions(image, rank=4)
 701 
 702     after_padding_width = target_width - offset_width - width
 703 
 704     after_padding_height = target_height - offset_height - height
 705 
 706     assert_ops += _assert(offset_height >= 0, ValueError,
 707                           'offset_height must be >= 0')
 708     assert_ops += _assert(offset_width >= 0, ValueError,
 709                           'offset_width must be >= 0')
 710     assert_ops += _assert(after_padding_width >= 0, ValueError,
 711                           'width must be <= target - offset')
 712     assert_ops += _assert(after_padding_height >= 0, ValueError,
 713                           'height must be <= target - offset')
 714     image = control_flow_ops.with_dependencies(assert_ops, image)
 715 
 716     # Do not pad on the depth dimensions.
 717     paddings = array_ops.reshape(
 718         array_ops.stack([
 719             0, 0, offset_height, after_padding_height, offset_width,
 720             after_padding_width, 0, 0
 721         ]), [4, 2])
 722     padded = array_ops.pad(image, paddings)
 723 
 724     padded_shape = [
 725         None if _is_tensor(i) else i
 726         for i in [batch, target_height, target_width, depth]
 727     ]
 728     padded.set_shape(padded_shape)
 729 
 730     if not is_batch:
 731       padded = array_ops.squeeze(padded, axis=[0])
 732 
 733     return padded
 734

 736 @tf_export('image.crop_to_bounding_box')
 737 def crop_to_bounding_box(image, offset_height, offset_width, target_height,
 738                          target_width):
 739   """Crops an image to a specified bounding box.
 740 
 741   This op cuts a rectangular part out of `image`. The top-left corner of the
 742   returned image is at `offset_height, offset_width` in `image`, and its
 743   lower-right corner is at
 744   `offset_height + target_height, offset_width + target_width`.
 745 
 746   Args:
 747     image: 4-D Tensor of shape `[batch, height, width, channels]` or
 748            3-D Tensor of shape `[height, width, channels]`.
 749     offset_height: Vertical coordinate of the top-left corner of the result in
 750                    the input.
 751     offset_width: Horizontal coordinate of the top-left corner of the result in
 752                   the input.
 753     target_height: Height of the result.
 754     target_width: Width of the result.
 755 
 756   Returns:
 757     If `image` was 4-D, a 4-D float Tensor of shape
 758     `[batch, target_height, target_width, channels]`
 759     If `image` was 3-D, a 3-D float Tensor of shape
 760     `[target_height, target_width, channels]`
 761 
 762   Raises:
 763     ValueError: If the shape of `image` is incompatible with the `offset_*` or
 764       `target_*` arguments, or either `offset_height` or `offset_width` is
 765       negative, or either `target_height` or `target_width` is not positive.
 766   """
 767   with ops.name_scope(None, 'crop_to_bounding_box', [image]):
 768     image = ops.convert_to_tensor(image, name='image')
 769 
 770     is_batch = True
 771     image_shape = image.get_shape()
 772     if image_shape.ndims == 3:
 773       is_batch = False
 774       image = array_ops.expand_dims(image, 0)
 775     elif image_shape.ndims is None:
 776       is_batch = False
 777       image = array_ops.expand_dims(image, 0)
 778       image.set_shape([None] * 4)
 779     elif image_shape.ndims != 4:
 780       raise ValueError('\'image\' must have either 3 or 4 dimensions.')
 781 
 782     assert_ops = _CheckAtLeast3DImage(image, require_static=False)
 783 
 784     batch, height, width, depth = _ImageDimensions(image, rank=4)
 785 
 786     assert_ops += _assert(offset_width >= 0, ValueError,
 787                           'offset_width must be >= 0.')
 788     assert_ops += _assert(offset_height >= 0, ValueError,
 789                           'offset_height must be >= 0.')
 790     assert_ops += _assert(target_width > 0, ValueError,
 791                           'target_width must be > 0.')
 792     assert_ops += _assert(target_height > 0, ValueError,
 793                           'target_height must be > 0.')
 794     assert_ops += _assert(width >= (target_width + offset_width), ValueError,
 795                           'width must be >= target + offset.')
 796     assert_ops += _assert(height >= (target_height + offset_height), ValueError,
 797                           'height must be >= target + offset.')
 798     image = control_flow_ops.with_dependencies(assert_ops, image)
 799 
 800     cropped = array_ops.slice(
 801         image, array_ops.stack([0, offset_height, offset_width, 0]),
 802         array_ops.stack([-1, target_height, target_width, -1]))
 803 
 804     cropped_shape = [
 805         None if _is_tensor(i) else i
 806         for i in [batch, target_height, target_width, depth]
 807     ]
 808     cropped.set_shape(cropped_shape)
 809 
 810     if not is_batch:
 811       cropped = array_ops.squeeze(cropped, axis=[0])
 812 
 813     return cropped

 816 @tf_export('image.resize_image_with_crop_or_pad')
 817 def resize_image_with_crop_or_pad(image, target_height, target_width):
 818   """Crops and/or pads an image to a target width and height.
 819 
 820   Resizes an image to a target width and height by either centrally
 821   cropping the image or padding it evenly with zeros.
 822 
 823   If `width` or `height` is greater than the specified `target_width` or
 824   `target_height` respectively, this op centrally crops along that dimension.
 825   If `width` or `height` is smaller than the specified `target_width` or
 826   `target_height` respectively, this op centrally pads with 0 along that
 827   dimension.
 828 
 829   Args:
 830     image: 4-D Tensor of shape `[batch, height, width, channels]` or
 831            3-D Tensor of shape `[height, width, channels]`.
 832     target_height: Target height.
 833     target_width: Target width.
 834 
 835   Raises:
 836     ValueError: if `target_height` or `target_width` are zero or negative.
 837 
 838   Returns:
 839     Cropped and/or padded image.
 840     If `images` was 4-D, a 4-D float Tensor of shape
 841     `[batch, new_height, new_width, channels]`.
 842     If `images` was 3-D, a 3-D float Tensor of shape
 843     `[new_height, new_width, channels]`.
 844   """
 845   with ops.name_scope(None, 'resize_image_with_crop_or_pad', [image]):
 846     image = ops.convert_to_tensor(image, name='image')
 847     image_shape = image.get_shape()
 848     is_batch = True
 849     if image_shape.ndims == 3:
 850       is_batch = False
 851       image = array_ops.expand_dims(image, 0)
 852     elif image_shape.ndims is None:
 853       is_batch = False
 854       image = array_ops.expand_dims(image, 0)
 855       image.set_shape([None] * 4)
 856     elif image_shape.ndims != 4:
 857       raise ValueError('\'image\' must have either 3 or 4 dimensions.')
 858 
 859     assert_ops = _CheckAtLeast3DImage(image, require_static=False)
 860     assert_ops += _assert(target_width > 0, ValueError,
 861                           'target_width must be > 0.')
 862     assert_ops += _assert(target_height > 0, ValueError,
 863                           'target_height must be > 0.')
 864 
 865     image = control_flow_ops.with_dependencies(assert_ops, image)
 866     # `crop_to_bounding_box` and `pad_to_bounding_box` have their own checks.
 867     # Make sure our checks come first, so that error messages are clearer.
 868     if _is_tensor(target_height):
 869       target_height = control_flow_ops.with_dependencies(
 870           assert_ops, target_height)
 871     if _is_tensor(target_width):
 872       target_width = control_flow_ops.with_dependencies(assert_ops,
 873                                                         target_width)
 874 
 875     def max_(x, y):
 876       if _is_tensor(x) or _is_tensor(y):
 877         return math_ops.maximum(x, y)
 878       else:
 879         return max(x, y)
 880 
 881     def min_(x, y):
 882       if _is_tensor(x) or _is_tensor(y):
 883         return math_ops.minimum(x, y)
 884       else:
 885         return min(x, y)
 886 
 887     def equal_(x, y):
 888       if _is_tensor(x) or _is_tensor(y):
 889         return math_ops.equal(x, y)
 890       else:
 891         return x == y
 892 
 893     _, height, width, _ = _ImageDimensions(image, rank=4)
 894     width_diff = target_width - width
 895     offset_crop_width = max_(-width_diff // 2, 0)
 896     offset_pad_width = max_(width_diff // 2, 0)
 897 
 898     height_diff = target_height - height
 899     offset_crop_height = max_(-height_diff // 2, 0)
 900     offset_pad_height = max_(height_diff // 2, 0)
 901 
 902     # Maybe crop if needed.
 903     cropped = crop_to_bounding_box(image, offset_crop_height, offset_crop_width,
 904                                    min_(target_height, height),
 905                                    min_(target_width, width))
 906 
 907     # Maybe pad if needed.
 908     resized = pad_to_bounding_box(cropped, offset_pad_height, offset_pad_width,
 909                                   target_height, target_width)
 910 
 911     # In theory all the checks below are redundant.
 912     if resized.get_shape().ndims is None:
 913       raise ValueError('resized contains no shape.')
 914 
 915     _, resized_height, resized_width, _ = _ImageDimensions(resized, rank=4)
 916 
 917     assert_ops = []
 918     assert_ops += _assert(
 919         equal_(resized_height, target_height), ValueError,
 920         'resized height is not correct.')
 921     assert_ops += _assert(
 922         equal_(resized_width, target_width), ValueError,
 923         'resized width is not correct.')
 924 
 925     resized = control_flow_ops.with_dependencies(assert_ops, resized)
 926 
 927     if not is_batch:
 928       resized = array_ops.squeeze(resized, axis=[0])
 929 
 930     return resized
 931

 933 @tf_export('image.ResizeMethod')
 934 class ResizeMethod(object):
 935   BILINEAR = 0
 936   NEAREST_NEIGHBOR = 1
 937   BICUBIC = 2
 938   AREA = 3

 941 @tf_export('image.resize_images')
 942 def resize_images(images,
 943                   size,
 944                   method=ResizeMethod.BILINEAR,
 945                   align_corners=False,
 946                   preserve_aspect_ratio=False):
 947   """Resize `images` to `size` using the specified `method`.
 948 
 949   Resized images will be distorted if their original aspect ratio is not
 950   the same as `size`.  To avoid distortions see
 951   `tf.image.resize_image_with_pad`.
 952 
 953   `method` can be one of:
 954 
 955   *   <b>`ResizeMethod.BILINEAR`</b>: [Bilinear interpolation.](
 956     https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Bilinear_interpolation)
 957   *   <b>`ResizeMethod.NEAREST_NEIGHBOR`</b>: [Nearest neighbor interpolation.](
 958     https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Nearest-neighbor_interpolation)
 959   *   <b>`ResizeMethod.BICUBIC`</b>: [Bicubic interpolation.](
 960     https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Bicubic_interpolation)
 961   *   <b>`ResizeMethod.AREA`</b>: Area interpolation.
 962 
 963   The return value has the same type as `images` if `method` is
 964   `ResizeMethod.NEAREST_NEIGHBOR`. It will also have the same type as `images`
 965   if the size of `images` can be statically determined to be the same as `size`,
 966   because `images` is returned in this case. Otherwise, the return value has
 967   type `float32`.
 968 
 969   Args:
 970     images: 4-D Tensor of shape `[batch, height, width, channels]` or
 971             3-D Tensor of shape `[height, width, channels]`.
 972     size: A 1-D int32 Tensor of 2 elements: `new_height, new_width`.  The
 973           new size for the images.
 974     method: ResizeMethod.  Defaults to `ResizeMethod.BILINEAR`.
 975     align_corners: bool.  If True, the centers of the 4 corner pixels of the
 976         input and output tensors are aligned, preserving the values at the
 977         corner pixels. Defaults to `False`.
 978     preserve_aspect_ratio: Whether to preserve the aspect ratio. If this is set,
 979       then `images` will be resized to a size that fits in `size` while
 980       preserving the aspect ratio of the original image. Scales up the image if
 981       `size` is bigger than the current size of the `image`. Defaults to False.
 982 
 983   Raises:
 984     ValueError: if the shape of `images` is incompatible with the
 985       shape arguments to this function
 986     ValueError: if `size` has invalid shape or type.
 987     ValueError: if an unsupported resize method is specified.
 988 
 989   Returns:
 990     If `images` was 4-D, a 4-D float Tensor of shape
 991     `[batch, new_height, new_width, channels]`.
 992     If `images` was 3-D, a 3-D float Tensor of shape
 993     `[new_height, new_width, channels]`.
 994   """
 995   with ops.name_scope(None, 'resize_images', [images, size]):
 996     images = ops.convert_to_tensor(images, name='images')
 997     if images.get_shape().ndims is None:
 998       raise ValueError('\'images\' contains no shape.')
 999     # TODO(shlens): Migrate this functionality to the underlying Op's.
1000     is_batch = True
1001     if images.get_shape().ndims == 3:
1002       is_batch = False
1003       images = array_ops.expand_dims(images, 0)
1004     elif images.get_shape().ndims != 4:
1005       raise ValueError('\'images\' must have either 3 or 4 dimensions.')
1006 
1007     _, height, width, _ = images.get_shape().as_list()
1008 
1009     try:
1010       size = ops.convert_to_tensor(size, dtypes.int32, name='size')
1011     except (TypeError, ValueError):
1012       raise ValueError('\'size\' must be a 1-D int32 Tensor')
1013     if not size.get_shape().is_compatible_with([2]):
1014       raise ValueError('\'size\' must be a 1-D Tensor of 2 elements: '
1015                        'new_height, new_width')
1016     size_const_as_shape = tensor_util.constant_value_as_shape(size)
1017     new_height_const = size_const_as_shape[0].value
1018     new_width_const = size_const_as_shape[1].value
1019 
1020     if preserve_aspect_ratio:
1021       # Get the current shapes of the image, even if dynamic.
1022       _, current_height, current_width, _ = _ImageDimensions(images, rank=4)
1023 
1024       # do the computation to find the right scale and height/width.
1025       scale_factor_height = (math_ops.to_float(new_height_const) /
1026                              math_ops.to_float(current_height))
1027       scale_factor_width = (math_ops.to_float(new_width_const) /
1028                             math_ops.to_float(current_width))
1029       scale_factor = math_ops.minimum(scale_factor_height, scale_factor_width)
1030       scaled_height_const = math_ops.to_int32(
1031           math_ops.round(scale_factor * math_ops.to_float(current_height)))
1032       scaled_width_const = math_ops.to_int32(
1033           math_ops.round(scale_factor * math_ops.to_float(current_width)))
1034 
1035       # NOTE: Reset the size and other constants used later.
1036       size = ops.convert_to_tensor([scaled_height_const, scaled_width_const],
1037                                    dtypes.int32, name='size')
1038       size_const_as_shape = tensor_util.constant_value_as_shape(size)
1039       new_height_const = size_const_as_shape[0].value
1040       new_width_const = size_const_as_shape[1].value
1041 
1042     # If we can determine that the height and width will be unmodified by this
1043     # transformation, we avoid performing the resize.
1044     if all(x is not None
1045            for x in [new_width_const, width, new_height_const, height]) and (
1046                width == new_width_const and height == new_height_const):
1047       if not is_batch:
1048         images = array_ops.squeeze(images, axis=[0])
1049       return images
1050 
1051     if method == ResizeMethod.BILINEAR:
1052       images = gen_image_ops.resize_bilinear(
1053           images, size, align_corners=align_corners)
1054     elif method == ResizeMethod.NEAREST_NEIGHBOR:
1055       images = gen_image_ops.resize_nearest_neighbor(
1056           images, size, align_corners=align_corners)
1057     elif method == ResizeMethod.BICUBIC:
1058       images = gen_image_ops.resize_bicubic(
1059           images, size, align_corners=align_corners)
1060     elif method == ResizeMethod.AREA:
1061       images = gen_image_ops.resize_area(
1062           images, size, align_corners=align_corners)
1063     else:
1064       raise ValueError('Resize method is not implemented.')
1065 
1066     # NOTE(mrry): The shape functions for the resize ops cannot unpack
1067     # the packed values in `new_size`, so set the shape here.
1068     images.set_shape([None, new_height_const, new_width_const, None])
1069 
1070     if not is_batch:
1071       images = array_ops.squeeze(images, axis=[0])
1072     return images
1073

1075 @tf_export('image.resize_image_with_pad')
1076 def resize_image_with_pad(image,
1077                           target_height,
1078                           target_width,
1079                           method=ResizeMethod.BILINEAR):
1080   """Resizes and pads an image to a target width and height.
1081 
1082   Resizes an image to a target width and height by keeping
1083   the aspect ratio the same without distortion. If the target
1084   dimensions don't match the image dimensions, the image
1085   is resized and then padded with zeroes to match requested
1086   dimensions.
1087 
1088   Args:
1089     image: 4-D Tensor of shape `[batch, height, width, channels]` or
1090            3-D Tensor of shape `[height, width, channels]`.
1091     target_height: Target height.
1092     target_width: Target width.
1093     method: Method to use for resizing image. See `resize_images()`
1094 
1095   Raises:
1096     ValueError: if `target_height` or `target_width` are zero or negative.
1097 
1098   Returns:
1099     Resized and padded image.
1100     If `images` was 4-D, a 4-D float Tensor of shape
1101     `[batch, new_height, new_width, channels]`.
1102     If `images` was 3-D, a 3-D float Tensor of shape
1103     `[new_height, new_width, channels]`.
1104   """
1105   with ops.name_scope(None, 'resize_image_with_pad', [image]):
1106     image = ops.convert_to_tensor(image, name='image')
1107     image_shape = image.get_shape()
1108     is_batch = True
1109     if image_shape.ndims == 3:
1110       is_batch = False
1111       image = array_ops.expand_dims(image, 0)
1112     elif image_shape.ndims is None:
1113       is_batch = False
1114       image = array_ops.expand_dims(image, 0)
1115       image.set_shape([None] * 4)
1116     elif image_shape.ndims != 4:
1117       raise ValueError('\'image\' must have either 3 or 4 dimensions.')
1118 
1119     assert_ops = _CheckAtLeast3DImage(image, require_static=False)
1120     assert_ops += _assert(target_width > 0, ValueError,
1121                           'target_width must be > 0.')
1122     assert_ops += _assert(target_height > 0, ValueError,
1123                           'target_height must be > 0.')
1124 
1125     image = control_flow_ops.with_dependencies(assert_ops, image)
1126 
1127     def max_(x, y):
1128       if _is_tensor(x) or _is_tensor(y):
1129         return math_ops.maximum(x, y)
1130       else:
1131         return max(x, y)
1132 
1133     _, height, width, _ = _ImageDimensions(image, rank=4)
1134 
1135     # convert values to float, to ease divisions
1136     f_height = math_ops.cast(height, dtype=dtypes.float64)
1137     f_width = math_ops.cast(width, dtype=dtypes.float64)
1138     f_target_height = math_ops.cast(target_height, dtype=dtypes.float64)
1139     f_target_width = math_ops.cast(target_width, dtype=dtypes.float64)
1140 
1141     # Find the ratio by which the image must be adjusted
1142     # to fit within the target
1143     ratio = max_(f_width / f_target_width, f_height / f_target_height)
1144     resized_height_float = f_height / ratio
1145     resized_width_float = f_width / ratio
1146     resized_height = math_ops.cast(
1147         math_ops.floor(resized_height_float), dtype=dtypes.int32)
1148     resized_width = math_ops.cast(
1149         math_ops.floor(resized_width_float), dtype=dtypes.int32)
1150 
1151     padding_height = (f_target_height - resized_height_float) / 2
1152     padding_width = (f_target_width - resized_width_float) / 2
1153     f_padding_height = math_ops.floor(padding_height)
1154     f_padding_width = math_ops.floor(padding_width)
1155     p_height = max_(0, math_ops.cast(f_padding_height, dtype=dtypes.int32))
1156     p_width = max_(0, math_ops.cast(f_padding_width, dtype=dtypes.int32))
1157 
1158     # Resize first, then pad to meet requested dimensions
1159     resized = resize_images(image, [resized_height, resized_width], method)
1160 
1161     padded = pad_to_bounding_box(resized, p_height, p_width, target_height,
1162                                  target_width)
1163 
1164     if padded.get_shape().ndims is None:
1165       raise ValueError('padded contains no shape.')
1166 
1167     _ImageDimensions(padded, rank=4)
1168 
1169     if not is_batch:
1170       padded = array_ops.squeeze(padded, axis=[0])
1171 
1172     return padded

1175 @tf_export('image.per_image_standardization')
1176 def per_image_standardization(image):
1177   """Linearly scales `image` to have zero mean and unit variance.
1178 
1179   This op computes `(x - mean) / adjusted_stddev`, where `mean` is the average
1180   of all values in image, and
1181   `adjusted_stddev = max(stddev, 1.0/sqrt(image.NumElements()))`.
1182 
1183   `stddev` is the standard deviation of all values in `image`. It is capped
1184   away from zero to protect against division by 0 when handling uniform images.
1185 
1186   Args:
1187     image: 3-D tensor of shape `[height, width, channels]`.
1188 
1189   Returns:
1190     The standardized image with same shape as `image`.
1191 
1192   Raises:
1193     ValueError: if the shape of 'image' is incompatible with this function.
1194   """
1195   with ops.name_scope(None, 'per_image_standardization', [image]) as scope:
1196     image = ops.convert_to_tensor(image, name='image')
1197     image = _Assert3DImage(image)
1198     num_pixels = math_ops.reduce_prod(array_ops.shape(image))
1199 
1200     image = math_ops.cast(image, dtype=dtypes.float32)
1201     image_mean = math_ops.reduce_mean(image)
1202 
1203     variance = (
1204         math_ops.reduce_mean(math_ops.square(image)) -
1205         math_ops.square(image_mean))
1206     variance = gen_nn_ops.relu(variance)
1207     stddev = math_ops.sqrt(variance)
1208 
1209     # Apply a minimum normalization that protects us against uniform images.
1210     min_stddev = math_ops.rsqrt(math_ops.cast(num_pixels, dtypes.float32))
1211     pixel_value_scale = math_ops.maximum(stddev, min_stddev)
1212     pixel_value_offset = image_mean
1213 
1214     image = math_ops.subtract(image, pixel_value_offset)
1215     image = math_ops.div(image, pixel_value_scale, name=scope)
1216     return image

1351 @tf_export('image.adjust_gamma')
1352 def adjust_gamma(image, gamma=1, gain=1):
1353   """Performs Gamma Correction on the input image.
1354 
1355   Also known as Power Law Transform. This function transforms the
1356   input image pixelwise according to the equation `Out = In**gamma`
1357   after scaling each pixel to the range 0 to 1.
1358 
1359   Args:
1360     image : A Tensor.
1361     gamma : A scalar or tensor. Non negative real number.
1362     gain  : A scalar or tensor. The constant multiplier.
1363 
1364   Returns:
1365     A Tensor. Gamma corrected output image.
1366 
1367   Raises:
1368     ValueError: If gamma is negative.
1369 
1370   Notes:
1371     For gamma greater than 1, the histogram will shift towards left and
1372     the output image will be darker than the input image.
1373     For gamma less than 1, the histogram will shift towards right and
1374     the output image will be brighter than the input image.
1375 
1376   References:
1377     [1] http://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Gamma_correction
1378   """
1379 
1380   with ops.name_scope(None, 'adjust_gamma', [image, gamma, gain]) as name:
1381     # Convert pixel value to DT_FLOAT for computing adjusted image.
1382     img = ops.convert_to_tensor(image, name='img', dtype=dtypes.float32)
1383     # Keep image dtype for computing the scale of corresponding dtype.
1384     image = ops.convert_to_tensor(image, name='image')
1385 
1386     assert_op = _assert(gamma >= 0, ValueError,
1387                         'Gamma should be a non-negative real number.')
1388     if assert_op:
1389       gamma = control_flow_ops.with_dependencies(assert_op, gamma)
1390 
1391     # scale = max(dtype) - min(dtype).
1392     scale = constant_op.constant(
1393         image.dtype.limits[1] - image.dtype.limits[0], dtype=dtypes.float32)
1394     # According to the definition of gamma correction.
1395     adjusted_img = (img / scale)**gamma * scale * gain
1396 
1397     return adjusted_img

1400 @tf_export('image.convert_image_dtype')
1401 def convert_image_dtype(image, dtype, saturate=False, name=None):
1402   """Convert `image` to `dtype`, scaling its values if needed.
1403 
1404   Images that are represented using floating point values are expected to have
1405   values in the range [0,1). Image data stored in integer data types are
1406   expected to have values in the range `[0,MAX]`, where `MAX` is the largest
1407   positive representable number for the data type.
1408 
1409   This op converts between data types, scaling the values appropriately before
1410   casting.
1411 
1412   Note that converting from floating point inputs to integer types may lead to
1413   over/underflow problems. Set saturate to `True` to avoid such problem in
1414   problematic conversions. If enabled, saturation will clip the output into the
1415   allowed range before performing a potentially dangerous cast (and only before
1416   performing such a cast, i.e., when casting from a floating point to an integer
1417   type, and when casting from a signed to an unsigned type; `saturate` has no
1418   effect on casts between floats, or on casts that increase the type's range).
1419 
1420   Args:
1421     image: An image.
1422     dtype: A `DType` to convert `image` to.
1423     saturate: If `True`, clip the input before casting (if necessary).
1424     name: A name for this operation (optional).
1425 
1426   Returns:
1427     `image`, converted to `dtype`.
1428   """
1429   image = ops.convert_to_tensor(image, name='image')
1430   if dtype == image.dtype:
1431     return array_ops.identity(image, name=name)
1432 
1433   with ops.name_scope(name, 'convert_image', [image]) as name:
1434     # Both integer: use integer multiplication in the larger range
1435     if image.dtype.is_integer and dtype.is_integer:
1436       scale_in = image.dtype.max
1437       scale_out = dtype.max
1438       if scale_in > scale_out:
1439         # Scaling down, scale first, then cast. The scaling factor will
1440         # cause in.max to be mapped to above out.max but below out.max+1,
1441         # so that the output is safely in the supported range.
1442         scale = (scale_in + 1) // (scale_out + 1)
1443         scaled = math_ops.div(image, scale)
1444 
1445         if saturate:
1446           return math_ops.saturate_cast(scaled, dtype, name=name)
1447         else:
1448           return math_ops.cast(scaled, dtype, name=name)
1449       else:
1450         # Scaling up, cast first, then scale. The scale will not map in.max to
1451         # out.max, but converting back and forth should result in no change.
1452         if saturate:
1453           cast = math_ops.saturate_cast(image, dtype)
1454         else:
1455           cast = math_ops.cast(image, dtype)
1456         scale = (scale_out + 1) // (scale_in + 1)
1457         return math_ops.multiply(cast, scale, name=name)
1458     elif image.dtype.is_floating and dtype.is_floating:
1459       # Both float: Just cast, no possible overflows in the allowed ranges.
1460       # Note: We're ignoreing float overflows. If your image dynamic range
1461       # exceeds float range you're on your own.
1462       return math_ops.cast(image, dtype, name=name)
1463     else:
1464       if image.dtype.is_integer:
1465         # Converting to float: first cast, then scale. No saturation possible.
1466         cast = math_ops.cast(image, dtype)
1467         scale = 1. / image.dtype.max
1468         return math_ops.multiply(cast, scale, name=name)
1469       else:
1470         # Converting from float: first scale, then cast
1471         scale = dtype.max + 0.5  # avoid rounding problems in the cast
1472         scaled = math_ops.multiply(image, scale)
1473         if saturate:
1474           return math_ops.saturate_cast(scaled, dtype, name=name)
1475         else:
1476           return math_ops.cast(scaled, dtype, name=name)
1477

1700   saturation_factor = random_ops.random_uniform([], lower, upper, seed=seed)

1729     orig_dtype = image.dtype
1730     flt_image = convert_image_dtype(image, dtypes.float32)

1773 @tf_export('image.decode_image')
1774 def decode_image(contents, channels=None, dtype=dtypes.uint8, name=None):
1775   """Convenience function for `decode_bmp`, `decode_gif`, `decode_jpeg`,
1776   and `decode_png`.
1777 
1778   Detects whether an image is a BMP, GIF, JPEG, or PNG, and performs the
1779   appropriate operation to convert the input bytes `string` into a `Tensor`
1780   of type `dtype`.
1781 
1782   Note: `decode_gif` returns a 4-D array `[num_frames, height, width, 3]`, as
1783   opposed to `decode_bmp`, `decode_jpeg` and `decode_png`, which return 3-D
1784   arrays `[height, width, num_channels]`. Make sure to take this into account
1785   when constructing your graph if you are intermixing GIF files with BMP, JPEG,
1786   and/or PNG files.
1787 
1788   Args:
1789     contents: 0-D `string`. The encoded image bytes.
1790     channels: An optional `int`. Defaults to `0`. Number of color channels for
1791       the decoded image.
1792     dtype: The desired DType of the returned `Tensor`.
1793     name: A name for the operation (optional)
1794 
1795   Returns:
1796     `Tensor` with type `dtype` and shape `[height, width, num_channels]` for
1797       BMP, JPEG, and PNG images and shape `[num_frames, height, width, 3]` for
1798       GIF images.
1799 
1800   Raises:
1801     ValueError: On incorrect number of channels.
1802   """
1803   with ops.name_scope(name, 'decode_image'):
1804     if channels not in (None, 0, 1, 3, 4):
1805       raise ValueError('channels must be in (None, 0, 1, 3, 4)')
1806     substr = string_ops.substr(contents, 0, 3)
1807 
1808     def _bmp():
1809       """Decodes a GIF image."""
1810       signature = string_ops.substr(contents, 0, 2)
1811       # Create assert op to check that bytes are BMP decodable
1812       is_bmp = math_ops.equal(signature, 'BM', name='is_bmp')
1813       decode_msg = 'Unable to decode bytes as JPEG, PNG, GIF, or BMP'
1814       assert_decode = control_flow_ops.Assert(is_bmp, [decode_msg])
1815       bmp_channels = 0 if channels is None else channels
1816       good_channels = math_ops.not_equal(bmp_channels, 1, name='check_channels')
1817       channels_msg = 'Channels must be in (None, 0, 3) when decoding BMP images'
1818       assert_channels = control_flow_ops.Assert(good_channels, [channels_msg])
1819       with ops.control_dependencies([assert_decode, assert_channels]):
1820         return convert_image_dtype(gen_image_ops.decode_bmp(contents), dtype)
1821 
1822     def _gif():
1823       # Create assert to make sure that channels is not set to 1
1824       # Already checked above that channels is in (None, 0, 1, 3)
1825 
1826       gif_channels = 0 if channels is None else channels
1827       good_channels = math_ops.logical_and(
1828           math_ops.not_equal(gif_channels, 1, name='check_gif_channels'),
1829           math_ops.not_equal(gif_channels, 4, name='check_gif_channels'))
1830       channels_msg = 'Channels must be in (None, 0, 3) when decoding GIF images'
1831       assert_channels = control_flow_ops.Assert(good_channels, [channels_msg])
1832       with ops.control_dependencies([assert_channels]):
1833         return convert_image_dtype(gen_image_ops.decode_gif(contents), dtype)
1834 
1835     def check_gif():
1836       # Create assert op to check that bytes are GIF decodable
1837       is_gif = math_ops.equal(substr, b'\x47\x49\x46', name='is_gif')
1838       return control_flow_ops.cond(is_gif, _gif, _bmp, name='cond_gif')
1839 
1840     def _png():
1841       """Decodes a PNG image."""
1842       return convert_image_dtype(
1843           gen_image_ops.decode_png(contents, channels,
1844                                    dtype=dtypes.uint8
1845                                    if dtype == dtypes.uint8
1846                                    else dtypes.uint16), dtype)
1847 
1848     def check_png():
1849       """Checks if an image is PNG."""
1850       return control_flow_ops.cond(
1851           _is_png(contents), _png, check_gif, name='cond_png')
1852 
1853     def _jpeg():
1854       """Decodes a jpeg image."""
1855       jpeg_channels = 0 if channels is None else channels
1856       good_channels = math_ops.not_equal(
1857           jpeg_channels, 4, name='check_jpeg_channels')
1858       channels_msg = ('Channels must be in (None, 0, 1, 3) when decoding JPEG '
1859                       'images')
1860       assert_channels = control_flow_ops.Assert(good_channels, [channels_msg])
1861       with ops.control_dependencies([assert_channels]):
1862         return convert_image_dtype(
1863             gen_image_ops.decode_jpeg(contents, channels), dtype)
1864 
1865     # Decode normal JPEG images (start with \xff\xd8\xff\xe0)
1866     # as well as JPEG images with EXIF data (start with \xff\xd8\xff\xe1).
1867     return control_flow_ops.cond(
1868         is_jpeg(contents), _jpeg, check_png, name='cond_jpeg')
1869

1871 @tf_export('image.total_variation')
1872 def total_variation(images, name=None):
1873   """Calculate and return the total variation for one or more images.
1874 
1875   The total variation is the sum of the absolute differences for neighboring
1876   pixel-values in the input images. This measures how much noise is in the
1877   images.
1878 
1879   This can be used as a loss-function during optimization so as to suppress
1880   noise in images. If you have a batch of images, then you should calculate
1881   the scalar loss-value as the sum:
1882   `loss = tf.reduce_sum(tf.image.total_variation(images))`
1883 
1884   This implements the anisotropic 2-D version of the formula described here:
1885 
1886   https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Total_variation_denoising
1887 
1888   Args:
1889     images: 4-D Tensor of shape `[batch, height, width, channels]` or
1890             3-D Tensor of shape `[height, width, channels]`.
1891 
1892     name: A name for the operation (optional).
1893 
1894   Raises:
1895     ValueError: if images.shape is not a 3-D or 4-D vector.
1896 
1897   Returns:
1898     The total variation of `images`.
1899 
1900     If `images` was 4-D, return a 1-D float Tensor of shape `[batch]` with the
1901     total variation for each image in the batch.
1902     If `images` was 3-D, return a scalar float with the total variation for
1903     that image.
1904   """
1905 
1906   with ops.name_scope(name, 'total_variation'):
1907     ndims = images.get_shape().ndims
1908 
1909     if ndims == 3:
1910       # The input is a single image with shape [height, width, channels].
1911 
1912       # Calculate the difference of neighboring pixel-values.
1913       # The images are shifted one pixel along the height and width by slicing.
1914       pixel_dif1 = images[1:, :, :] - images[:-1, :, :]
1915       pixel_dif2 = images[:, 1:, :] - images[:, :-1, :]
1916 
1917       # Sum for all axis. (None is an alias for all axis.)
1918       sum_axis = None
1919     elif ndims == 4:
1920       # The input is a batch of images with shape:
1921       # [batch, height, width, channels].
1922 
1923       # Calculate the difference of neighboring pixel-values.
1924       # The images are shifted one pixel along the height and width by slicing.
1925       pixel_dif1 = images[:, 1:, :, :] - images[:, :-1, :, :]
1926       pixel_dif2 = images[:, :, 1:, :] - images[:, :, :-1, :]
1927 
1928       # Only sum for the last 3 axis.
1929       # This results in a 1-D tensor with the total variation for each image.
1930       sum_axis = [1, 2, 3]
1931     else:
1932       raise ValueError('\'images\' must be either 3 or 4-dimensional.')
1933 
1934     # Calculate the total variation by taking the absolute value of the
1935     # pixel-differences and summing over the appropriate axis.
1936     tot_var = (
1937         math_ops.reduce_sum(math_ops.abs(pixel_dif1), axis=sum_axis) +
1938         math_ops.reduce_sum(math_ops.abs(pixel_dif2), axis=sum_axis))
1939 
1940   return tot_var

1954   """Generate a single randomly distorted bounding box for an image.

1956   Bounding box annotations are often supplied in addition to ground-truth labels
1957   in image recognition or object localization tasks. A common technique for
1958   training such a system is to randomly distort an image while preserving

1960   localization of an object, i.e. bounding box, given an `image_size`,

1971   The
1972   bounding box coordinates are floats in `[0.0, 1.0]` relative to the width and

1974 
1975   For example,
1976 
1977   ```python

1994   `use_image_if_no_bounding_boxes = true` will assume there is a single implicit

1996   false and no bounding boxes are supplied, an error is raised.

2008         random

2011       A second seed to avoid seed collision.

2015         be

2017       any of the bounding boxes supplied.

2019       1.33]`.
2020       The cropped area of the image must have an aspect ratio =
2021       width / height within this range.
2022     area_range: An optional list of `floats`. Defaults to `[0.05, 1]`.

2036

2038     A tuple of `Tensor` objects (begin, size, bboxes).
2039 
2040     begin: A `Tensor`. Has the same type as `image_size`. 1-D, containing
2041     `[offset_height, offset_width, 0]`. Provide as input to
2042       `tf.slice`.
2043     size: A `Tensor`. Has the same type as `image_size`. 1-D, containing
2044     `[target_height, target_width, -1]`. Provide as input to
2045       `tf.slice`.
2046     bboxes: A `Tensor` of type `float32`. 3-D with shape `[1, 1, 4]` containing
2047     the distorted bounding box.
2048       Provide as input to `tf.image.draw_bounding_boxes`.
2049   """
2050   with ops.name_scope(name, 'sample_distorted_bounding_box'):
2051     return gen_image_ops.sample_distorted_bounding_box_v2(
2052         image_size,
2053         bounding_boxes,
2054         seed=seed,
2055         seed2=seed2,
2056         min_object_covered=min_object_covered,

2064 @tf_export('image.non_max_suppression')

2071   """Greedily selects a subset of bounding boxes in descending order of score.
2072 
2073   Prunes away boxes that have high intersection-over-union (IOU) overlap

2076   diagonal pair of box corners and the coordinates can be provided as normalized
2077   (i.e., lying in the interval [0, 1]) or absolute.  Note that this algorithm
2078   is agnostic to where the origin is in the coordinate system.  Note that this
2079   algorithm is invariant to orthogonal transformations and translations

2081   system result in the same boxes being selected by the algorithm.

2097       overlap too much with respect to IOU.
2098     score_threshold: A float representing the threshold for deciding when to

2107     iou_threshold = ops.convert_to_tensor(iou_threshold, name='iou_threshold')
2108     score_threshold = ops.convert_to_tensor(
2109         score_threshold, name='score_threshold')

2324 def _verify_compatible_image_shapes(img1, img2):
2325   """Checks if two image tensors are compatible for applying SSIM or PSNR.
2326 
2327   This function checks if two sets of images have ranks at least 3, and if the
2328   last three dimensions match.
2329 
2330   Args:
2331     img1: Tensor containing the first image batch.
2332     img2: Tensor containing the second image batch.
2333 
2334   Returns:
2335     A tuple containing: the first tensor shape, the second tensor shape, and a
2336     list of control_flow_ops.Assert() ops implementing the checks.
2337 
2338   Raises:
2339     ValueError: When static shape check fails.
2340   """
2341   shape1 = img1.get_shape().with_rank_at_least(3)
2342   shape2 = img2.get_shape().with_rank_at_least(3)
2343   shape1[-3:].assert_is_compatible_with(shape2[-3:])
2344 
2345   if shape1.ndims is not None and shape2.ndims is not None:
2346     for dim1, dim2 in zip(reversed(shape1[:-3]), reversed(shape2[:-3])):
2347       if not (dim1 == 1 or dim2 == 1 or dim1.is_compatible_with(dim2)):
2348         raise ValueError(
2349             'Two images are not compatible: %s and %s' % (shape1, shape2))
2350 
2351   # Now assign shape tensors.
2352   shape1, shape2 = array_ops.shape_n([img1, img2])
2353 
2354   # TODO(sjhwang): Check if shape1[:-3] and shape2[:-3] are broadcastable.
2355   checks = []
2356   checks.append(control_flow_ops.Assert(
2357       math_ops.greater_equal(array_ops.size(shape1), 3),
2358       [shape1, shape2], summarize=10))
2359   checks.append(control_flow_ops.Assert(
2360       math_ops.reduce_all(math_ops.equal(shape1[-3:], shape2[-3:])),
2361       [shape1, shape2], summarize=10))
2362   return shape1, shape2, checks

2365 @tf_export('image.psnr')
2366 def psnr(a, b, max_val, name=None):
2367   """Returns the Peak Signal-to-Noise Ratio between a and b.
2368 
2369   This is intended to be used on signals (or images). Produces a PSNR value for
2370   each image in batch.
2371 
2372   The last three dimensions of input are expected to be [height, width, depth].
2373 
2374   Example:
2375 
2376   ```python
2377       # Read images from file.
2378       im1 = tf.decode_png('path/to/im1.png')
2379       im2 = tf.decode_png('path/to/im2.png')
2380       # Compute PSNR over tf.uint8 Tensors.
2381       psnr1 = tf.image.psnr(im1, im2, max_val=255)
2382 
2383       # Compute PSNR over tf.float32 Tensors.
2384       im1 = tf.image.convert_image_dtype(im1, tf.float32)
2385       im2 = tf.image.convert_image_dtype(im2, tf.float32)
2386       psnr2 = tf.image.psnr(im1, im2, max_val=1.0)
2387       # psnr1 and psnr2 both have type tf.float32 and are almost equal.
2388   ```
2389 
2390   Arguments:
2391     a: First set of images.
2392     b: Second set of images.
2393     max_val: The dynamic range of the images (i.e., the difference between the
2394       maximum the and minimum allowed values).
2395     name: Namespace to embed the computation in.
2396 
2397   Returns:
2398     The scalar PSNR between a and b. The returned tensor has type `tf.float32`
2399     and shape [batch_size, 1].
2400   """
2401   with ops.name_scope(name, 'PSNR', [a, b]):
2402     # Need to convert the images to float32.  Scale max_val accordingly so that
2403     # PSNR is computed correctly.
2404     max_val = math_ops.cast(max_val, a.dtype)
2405     max_val = convert_image_dtype(max_val, dtypes.float32)
2406     a = convert_image_dtype(a, dtypes.float32)
2407     b = convert_image_dtype(b, dtypes.float32)
2408     mse = math_ops.reduce_mean(math_ops.squared_difference(a, b), [-3, -2, -1])
2409     psnr_val = math_ops.subtract(
2410         20 * math_ops.log(max_val) / math_ops.log(10.0),
2411         np.float32(10 / np.log(10)) * math_ops.log(mse),
2412         name='psnr')
2413 
2414     _, _, checks = _verify_compatible_image_shapes(a, b)
2415     with ops.control_dependencies(checks):
2416       return array_ops.identity(psnr_val)
2417 
2418 _SSIM_K1 = 0.01
2419 _SSIM_K2 = 0.03

2422 def _ssim_helper(x, y, reducer, max_val, compensation=1.0):
2423   r"""Helper function for computing SSIM.
2424 
2425   SSIM estimates covariances with weighted sums.  The default parameters
2426   use a biased estimate of the covariance:
2427   Suppose `reducer` is a weighted sum, then the mean estimators are
2428     \mu_x = \sum_i w_i x_i,
2429     \mu_y = \sum_i w_i y_i,
2430   where w_i's are the weighted-sum weights, and covariance estimator is
2431     cov_{xy} = \sum_i w_i (x_i - \mu_x) (y_i - \mu_y)
2432   with assumption \sum_i w_i = 1. This covariance estimator is biased, since
2433     E[cov_{xy}] = (1 - \sum_i w_i ^ 2) Cov(X, Y).
2434   For SSIM measure with unbiased covariance estimators, pass as `compensation`
2435   argument (1 - \sum_i w_i ^ 2).
2436 
2437   Arguments:
2438     x: First set of images.
2439     y: Second set of images.
2440     reducer: Function that computes 'local' averages from set of images.
2441       For non-covolutional version, this is usually tf.reduce_mean(x, [1, 2]),
2442       and for convolutional version, this is usually tf.nn.avg_pool or
2443       tf.nn.conv2d with weighted-sum kernel.
2444     max_val: The dynamic range (i.e., the difference between the maximum
2445       possible allowed value and the minimum allowed value).
2446     compensation: Compensation factor. See above.
2447 
2448   Returns:
2449     A pair containing the luminance measure, and the contrast-structure measure.
2450   """
2451   c1 = (_SSIM_K1 * max_val) ** 2
2452   c2 = (_SSIM_K2 * max_val) ** 2
2453 
2454   # SSIM luminance measure is
2455   # (2 * mu_x * mu_y + c1) / (mu_x ** 2 + mu_y ** 2 + c1).
2456   mean0 = reducer(x)
2457   mean1 = reducer(y)
2458   num0 = mean0 * mean1 * 2.0
2459   den0 = math_ops.square(mean0) + math_ops.square(mean1)
2460   luminance = (num0 + c1) / (den0 + c1)
2461 
2462   # SSIM contrast-structure measure is
2463   #   (2 * cov_{xy} + c2) / (cov_{xx} + cov_{yy} + c2).
2464   # Note that `reducer` is a weighted sum with weight w_k, \sum_i w_i = 1, then
2465   #   cov_{xy} = \sum_i w_i (x_i - \mu_x) (y_i - \mu_y)
2466   #          = \sum_i w_i x_i y_i - (\sum_i w_i x_i) (\sum_j w_j y_j).
2467   num1 = reducer(x * y) * 2.0
2468   den1 = reducer(math_ops.square(x) + math_ops.square(y))
2469   c2 *= compensation
2470   cs = (num1 - num0 + c2) / (den1 - den0 + c2)
2471 
2472   # SSIM score is the product of the luminance and contrast-structure measures.
2473   return luminance, cs
2474

2476 def _fspecial_gauss(size, sigma):
2477   """Function to mimic the 'fspecial' gaussian MATLAB function."""
2478   size = ops.convert_to_tensor(size, dtypes.int32)
2479   sigma = ops.convert_to_tensor(sigma)
2480 
2481   coords = math_ops.cast(math_ops.range(size), sigma.dtype)
2482   coords -= math_ops.cast(size - 1, sigma.dtype) / 2.0
2483 
2484   g = math_ops.square(coords)
2485   g *= -0.5 / math_ops.square(sigma)
2486 
2487   g = array_ops.reshape(g, shape=[1, -1]) + array_ops.reshape(g, shape=[-1, 1])
2488   g = array_ops.reshape(g, shape=[1, -1])  # For tf.nn.softmax().
2489   g = nn_ops.softmax(g)
2490   return array_ops.reshape(g, shape=[size, size, 1, 1])

2493 def _ssim_per_channel(img1, img2, max_val=1.0):
2494   """Computes SSIM index between img1 and img2 per color channel.
2495 
2496   This function matches the standard SSIM implementation from:
2497   Wang, Z., Bovik, A. C., Sheikh, H. R., & Simoncelli, E. P. (2004). Image
2498   quality assessment: from error visibility to structural similarity. IEEE
2499   transactions on image processing.
2500 
2501   Details:
2502     - 11x11 Gaussian filter of width 1.5 is used.
2503     - k1 = 0.01, k2 = 0.03 as in the original paper.
2504 
2505   Args:
2506     img1: First image batch.
2507     img2: Second image batch.
2508     max_val: The dynamic range of the images (i.e., the difference between the
2509       maximum the and minimum allowed values).
2510 
2511   Returns:
2512     A pair of tensors containing and channel-wise SSIM and contrast-structure
2513     values. The shape is [..., channels].
2514   """
2515   filter_size = constant_op.constant(11, dtype=dtypes.int32)
2516   filter_sigma = constant_op.constant(1.5, dtype=img1.dtype)
2517 
2518   shape1, shape2 = array_ops.shape_n([img1, img2])
2519   checks = [
2520       control_flow_ops.Assert(math_ops.reduce_all(math_ops.greater_equal(
2521           shape1[-3:-1], filter_size)), [shape1, filter_size], summarize=8),
2522       control_flow_ops.Assert(math_ops.reduce_all(math_ops.greater_equal(
2523           shape2[-3:-1], filter_size)), [shape2, filter_size], summarize=8)]
2524 
2525   # Enforce the check to run before computation.
2526   with ops.control_dependencies(checks):
2527     img1 = array_ops.identity(img1)
2528 
2529   # TODO(sjhwang): Try to cache kernels and compensation factor.
2530   kernel = _fspecial_gauss(filter_size, filter_sigma)
2531   kernel = array_ops.tile(kernel, multiples=[1, 1, shape1[-1], 1])
2532 
2533   # The correct compensation factor is `1.0 - tf.reduce_sum(tf.square(kernel))`,
2534   # but to match MATLAB implementation of MS-SSIM, we use 1.0 instead.
2535   compensation = 1.0
2536 
2537   # TODO(sjhwang): Try FFT.
2538   # TODO(sjhwang): Gaussian kernel is separable in space. Consider applying
2539   #   1-by-n and n-by-1 Gaussain filters instead of an n-by-n filter.
2540   def reducer(x):
2541     shape = array_ops.shape(x)
2542     x = array_ops.reshape(x, shape=array_ops.concat([[-1], shape[-3:]], 0))
2543     y = nn.depthwise_conv2d(x, kernel, strides=[1, 1, 1, 1], padding='VALID')
2544     return array_ops.reshape(y, array_ops.concat([shape[:-3],
2545                                                   array_ops.shape(y)[1:]], 0))
2546 
2547   luminance, cs = _ssim_helper(img1, img2, reducer, max_val, compensation)
2548 
2549   # Average over the second and the third from the last: height, width.
2550   axes = constant_op.constant([-3, -2], dtype=dtypes.int32)
2551   ssim_val = math_ops.reduce_mean(luminance * cs, axes)
2552   cs = math_ops.reduce_mean(cs, axes)
2553   return ssim_val, cs

2556 @tf_export('image.ssim')
2557 def ssim(img1, img2, max_val):
2558   """Computes SSIM index between img1 and img2.
2559 
2560   This function is based on the standard SSIM implementation from:
2561   Wang, Z., Bovik, A. C., Sheikh, H. R., & Simoncelli, E. P. (2004). Image
2562   quality assessment: from error visibility to structural similarity. IEEE
2563   transactions on image processing.
2564 
2565   Note: The true SSIM is only defined on grayscale.  This function does not
2566   perform any colorspace transform.  (If input is already YUV, then it will
2567   compute YUV SSIM average.)
2568 
2569   Details:
2570     - 11x11 Gaussian filter of width 1.5 is used.
2571     - k1 = 0.01, k2 = 0.03 as in the original paper.
2572 
2573   The image sizes must be at least 11x11 because of the filter size.
2574 
2575   Example:
2576 
2577   ```python
2578       # Read images from file.
2579       im1 = tf.decode_png('path/to/im1.png')
2580       im2 = tf.decode_png('path/to/im2.png')
2581       # Compute SSIM over tf.uint8 Tensors.
2582       ssim1 = tf.image.ssim(im1, im2, max_val=255)
2583 
2584       # Compute SSIM over tf.float32 Tensors.
2585       im1 = tf.image.convert_image_dtype(im1, tf.float32)
2586       im2 = tf.image.convert_image_dtype(im2, tf.float32)
2587       ssim2 = tf.image.ssim(im1, im2, max_val=1.0)
2588       # ssim1 and ssim2 both have type tf.float32 and are almost equal.
2589   ```
2590 
2591   Args:
2592     img1: First image batch.
2593     img2: Second image batch.
2594     max_val: The dynamic range of the images (i.e., the difference between the
2595       maximum the and minimum allowed values).
2596 
2597   Returns:
2598     A tensor containing an SSIM value for each image in batch.  Returned SSIM
2599     values are in range (-1, 1], when pixel values are non-negative. Returns
2600     a tensor with shape: broadcast(img1.shape[:-3], img2.shape[:-3]).
2601   """
2602   _, _, checks = _verify_compatible_image_shapes(img1, img2)
2603   with ops.control_dependencies(checks):
2604     img1 = array_ops.identity(img1)
2605 
2606   # Need to convert the images to float32.  Scale max_val accordingly so that
2607   # SSIM is computed correctly.
2608   max_val = math_ops.cast(max_val, img1.dtype)
2609   max_val = convert_image_dtype(max_val, dtypes.float32)
2610   img1 = convert_image_dtype(img1, dtypes.float32)
2611   img2 = convert_image_dtype(img2, dtypes.float32)
2612   ssim_per_channel, _ = _ssim_per_channel(img1, img2, max_val)
2613   # Compute average over color channels.
2614   return math_ops.reduce_mean(ssim_per_channel, [-1])
2615 
2616 
2617 # Default values obtained by Wang et al.
2618 _MSSSIM_WEIGHTS = (0.0448, 0.2856, 0.3001, 0.2363, 0.1333)
2619
