2621 @tf_export('image.ssim_multiscale')
2622 def ssim_multiscale(img1, img2, max_val, power_factors=_MSSSIM_WEIGHTS):
2623   """Computes the MS-SSIM between img1 and img2.
2624 
2625   This function assumes that `img1` and `img2` are image batches, i.e. the last
2626   three dimensions are [height, width, channels].
2627 
2628   Note: The true SSIM is only defined on grayscale.  This function does not
2629   perform any colorspace transform.  (If input is already YUV, then it will
2630   compute YUV SSIM average.)
2631 
2632   Original paper: Wang, Zhou, Eero P. Simoncelli, and Alan C. Bovik. "Multiscale
2633   structural similarity for image quality assessment." Signals, Systems and
2634   Computers, 2004.
2635 
2636   Arguments:
2637     img1: First image batch.
2638     img2: Second image batch. Must have the same rank as img1.
2639     max_val: The dynamic range of the images (i.e., the difference between the
2640       maximum the and minimum allowed values).
2641     power_factors: Iterable of weights for each of the scales. The number of
2642       scales used is the length of the list. Index 0 is the unscaled
2643       resolution's weight and each increasing scale corresponds to the image
2644       being downsampled by 2.  Defaults to (0.0448, 0.2856, 0.3001, 0.2363,
2645       0.1333), which are the values obtained in the original paper.
2646 
2647   Returns:
2648     A tensor containing an MS-SSIM value for each image in batch.  The values
2649     are in range [0, 1].  Returns a tensor with shape:
2650     broadcast(img1.shape[:-3], img2.shape[:-3]).
2651   """
2652   # Shape checking.
2653   shape1 = img1.get_shape().with_rank_at_least(3)
2654   shape2 = img2.get_shape().with_rank_at_least(3)
2655   shape1[-3:].merge_with(shape2[-3:])
2656 
2657   with ops.name_scope(None, 'MS-SSIM', [img1, img2]):
2658     shape1, shape2, checks = _verify_compatible_image_shapes(img1, img2)
2659     with ops.control_dependencies(checks):
2660       img1 = array_ops.identity(img1)
2661 
2662     # Need to convert the images to float32.  Scale max_val accordingly so that
2663     # SSIM is computed correctly.
2664     max_val = math_ops.cast(max_val, img1.dtype)
2665     max_val = convert_image_dtype(max_val, dtypes.float32)
2666     img1 = convert_image_dtype(img1, dtypes.float32)
2667     img2 = convert_image_dtype(img2, dtypes.float32)
2668 
2669     imgs = [img1, img2]
2670     shapes = [shape1, shape2]
2671 
2672     # img1 and img2 are assumed to be a (multi-dimensional) batch of
2673     # 3-dimensional images (height, width, channels). `heads` contain the batch
2674     # dimensions, and `tails` contain the image dimensions.
2675     heads = [s[:-3] for s in shapes]
2676     tails = [s[-3:] for s in shapes]
2677 
2678     divisor = [1, 2, 2, 1]
2679     divisor_tensor = constant_op.constant(divisor[1:], dtype=dtypes.int32)
2680 
2681     def do_pad(images, remainder):
2682       padding = array_ops.expand_dims(remainder, -1)
2683       padding = array_ops.pad(padding, [[1, 0], [1, 0]])
2684       return [array_ops.pad(x, padding, mode='SYMMETRIC') for x in images]
2685 
2686     mcs = []
2687     for k in range(len(power_factors)):
2688       with ops.name_scope(None, 'Scale%d' % k, imgs):
2689         if k > 0:
2690           # Avg pool takes rank 4 tensors. Flatten leading dimensions.
2691           flat_imgs = [
2692               array_ops.reshape(x, array_ops.concat([[-1], t], 0))
2693               for x, t in zip(imgs, tails)
2694           ]
2695 
2696           remainder = tails[0] % divisor_tensor
2697           need_padding = math_ops.reduce_any(math_ops.not_equal(remainder, 0))
2698           # pylint: disable=cell-var-from-loop
2699           padded = control_flow_ops.cond(need_padding,
2700                                          lambda: do_pad(flat_imgs, remainder),
2701                                          lambda: flat_imgs)
2702           # pylint: enable=cell-var-from-loop
2703 
2704           downscaled = [nn_ops.avg_pool(x, ksize=divisor, strides=divisor,
2705                                         padding='VALID')
2706                         for x in padded]
2707           tails = [x[1:] for x in array_ops.shape_n(downscaled)]
2708           imgs = [
2709               array_ops.reshape(x, array_ops.concat([h, t], 0))
2710               for x, h, t in zip(downscaled, heads, tails)
2711           ]
2712 
2713         # Overwrite previous ssim value since we only need the last one.
2714         ssim_per_channel, cs = _ssim_per_channel(*imgs, max_val=max_val)
2715         mcs.append(nn_ops.relu(cs))
2716 
2717     # Remove the cs score for the last scale. In the MS-SSIM calculation,
2718     # we use the l(p) at the highest scale. l(p) * cs(p) is ssim(p).
2719     mcs.pop()  # Remove the cs score for the last scale.
2720     mcs_and_ssim = array_ops.stack(mcs + [nn_ops.relu(ssim_per_channel)],
2721                                    axis=-1)
2722     # Take weighted geometric mean across the scale axis.
2723     ms_ssim = math_ops.reduce_prod(math_ops.pow(mcs_and_ssim, power_factors),
2724                                    [-1])
2725 
2726     return math_ops.reduce_mean(ms_ssim, [-1])  # Avg over color channels.
2727 
2728 
2729 @tf_export('image.image_gradients')
2730 def image_gradients(image):
2731   """Returns image gradients (dy, dx) for each color channel.
2732 
2733   Both output tensors have the same shape as the input: [batch_size, h, w,
2734   d]. The gradient values are organized so that [I(x+1, y) - I(x, y)] is in
2735   location (x, y). That means that dy will always have zeros in the last row,
2736   and dx will always have zeros in the last column.
2737 
2738   Arguments:
2739     image: Tensor with shape [batch_size, h, w, d].
2740 
2741   Returns:
2742     Pair of tensors (dy, dx) holding the vertical and horizontal image
2743     gradients (1-step finite difference).
2744 
2745   Raises:
2746     ValueError: If `image` is not a 4D tensor.
2747   """
2748   if image.get_shape().ndims != 4:
2749     raise ValueError('image_gradients expects a 4D tensor '
2750                      '[batch_size, h, w, d], not %s.', image.get_shape())
2751   image_shape = array_ops.shape(image)
2752   batch_size, height, width, depth = array_ops.unstack(image_shape)
2753   dy = image[:, 1:, :, :] - image[:, :-1, :, :]
2754   dx = image[:, :, 1:, :] - image[:, :, :-1, :]
2755 
2756   # Return tensors with same size as original image by concatenating
2757   # zeros. Place the gradient [I(x+1,y) - I(x,y)] on the base pixel (x, y).
2758   shape = array_ops.stack([batch_size, 1, width, depth])
2759   dy = array_ops.concat([dy, array_ops.zeros(shape, image.dtype)], 1)
2760   dy = array_ops.reshape(dy, image_shape)
2761 
2762   shape = array_ops.stack([batch_size, height, 1, depth])
2763   dx = array_ops.concat([dx, array_ops.zeros(shape, image.dtype)], 2)
2764   dx = array_ops.reshape(dx, image_shape)
2765 
2766   return dy, dx
2767

2769 @tf_export('image.sobel_edges')
2770 def sobel_edges(image):
2771   """Returns a tensor holding Sobel edge maps.
2772 
2773   Arguments:
2774     image: Image tensor with shape [batch_size, h, w, d] and type float32 or
2775     float64.  The image(s) must be 2x2 or larger.
2776 
2777   Returns:
2778     Tensor holding edge maps for each channel. Returns a tensor with shape
2779     [batch_size, h, w, d, 2] where the last two dimensions hold [[dy[0], dx[0]],
2780     [dy[1], dx[1]], ..., [dy[d-1], dx[d-1]]] calculated using the Sobel filter.
2781   """
2782   # Define vertical and horizontal Sobel filters.
2783   static_image_shape = image.get_shape()
2784   image_shape = array_ops.shape(image)
2785   kernels = [[[-1, -2, -1], [0, 0, 0], [1, 2, 1]],
2786              [[-1, 0, 1], [-2, 0, 2], [-1, 0, 1]]]
2787   num_kernels = len(kernels)
2788   kernels = np.transpose(np.asarray(kernels), (1, 2, 0))
2789   kernels = np.expand_dims(kernels, -2)
2790   kernels_tf = constant_op.constant(kernels, dtype=image.dtype)
2791 
2792   kernels_tf = array_ops.tile(kernels_tf, [1, 1, image_shape[-1], 1],
2793                               name='sobel_filters')
2794 
2795   # Use depth-wise convolution to calculate edge maps per channel.
2796   pad_sizes = [[0, 0], [1, 1], [1, 1], [0, 0]]
2797   padded = array_ops.pad(image, pad_sizes, mode='REFLECT')
2798 
2799   # Output tensor has shape [batch_size, h, w, d * num_kernels].
2800   strides = [1, 1, 1, 1]
2801   output = nn.depthwise_conv2d(padded, kernels_tf, strides, 'VALID')
2802 
2803   # Reshape to [batch_size, h, w, d, num_kernels].
2804   shape = array_ops.concat([image_shape, [num_kernels]], 0)
2805   output = array_ops.reshape(output, shape=shape)
2806   output.set_shape(static_image_shape.concatenate([num_kernels]))
2807   return output
